    %a{:href => "https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/climate/maps-and-data/historic-station-data"}
      %p.label Weather data from the Met Office

    %p While these rising temperatures may not be immediately obvious in day to day life, once laid out on a graph they become clear. Over the last 50 years especially:

    %ul
      %li The hottest days are more hot
      %li The coldest days are less cold
      %li The average day is hotter than what it was 50-70 years ago

    %a{:href => "https://www.globalchange.gov/browse/indicator-details/3983"}
      %p Take a moment to think about the last few summers, particularly. Have you noticed that - generally speaking - the hottest day on a given summer is hotter than that of the year before? Have you noticed that heatwaves are more frequent and last longer?

    %a{:href => "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/dec/17/warmer-winters-climate-crisis-scientists"}
      %p Think of winter, too. Have you been seeing less ice and snow? Have you noticed that winter days are often warmer than what they were even five or ten years ago? Warm winters, as pleasant as they may seem at the time, are not normal - they can wreak havoc later in the year.

    %hr

    %p So, we know that climate change is here and that we can already feel it - which begs the question, who or what is responsible for carbon emissions? Where do changes need to be made?

    .pie
      %canvas#chart4

    %script{:src => "chart_4.js"}

    %a{:href => "https://ourworldindata.org/emissions-by-sector"}
      %p.label Data and description from Our World In Data

    %p What this data shows us is that emissions do not simply come from cars, or from electricity production, or from eating meat - emissions are a product of almost every facet of our everyday lives. In some sectors, there are net-zero solutions where implementation is the only remaining hurdle; in others, low-carbon technologies still need to be developed.

    

    %hr

    %a{:href => "https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2017/jul/10/100-fossil-fuel-companies-investors-responsible-71-global-emissions-cdp-study-climate-change"}
      %p Since 1988, just 100 companies have been responsible for more than 70% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions - most of these are coal or oil producers.

    %a{:href => "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2018/sep/19/shell-and-exxons-secret-1980s-climate-change-warnings"}
      %p Many of these companies knew about the dangers of climate change 40 years ago.

    %a{:href => "https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/22/top-oil-firms-spending-millions-lobbying-to-block-climate-change-policies-says-report"}
      %p But rather than investing early in renewable energy, these companies spend hundreds of millions a year lobbying against policies that would help curtail the same dangers they knew about decades ago.

    %a{:href => "https://www.undp.org/press-releases/every-dollar-pledged-tackle-climate-crisis-world%E2%80%99s-poor-four-dollars-are-spent"}
